WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.820
Music

2
00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:20.840
Traditionally in computation
and processing data

3
00:00:20.844 --> 00:00:23.772
we would bring the data to the computer.

4
00:00:23.772 --> 00:00:25.001
You'd wanna program

5
00:00:25.001 --> 00:00:27.767
and you'd bring the data into the program.

6
00:00:27.767 --> 00:00:29.755
In a big data cluster

7
00:00:29.755 --> 00:00:32.256
what Larry Page and Sergey Brin

8
00:00:32.256 --> 00:00:35.304
came up with is very pretty simple

9
00:00:35.304 --> 00:00:37.766
is they took the data and they sliced it

10
00:00:37.766 --> 00:00:40.260
into pieces and they distributed each

11
00:00:40.260 --> 00:00:42.320
and they replicated each piece

12
00:00:42.327 --> 00:00:43.740
or triplicated each piece

13
00:00:43.747 --> 00:00:45.939
and they would send it

14
00:00:45.939 --> 00:00:48.363
the pieces of these files

15
00:00:48.363 --> 00:00:50.983
to thousands of computers

16
00:00:50.983 --> 00:00:53.078
first it was hundreds but
then now it's thousands

17
00:00:53.078 --> 00:00:54.759
now it's tens of thousands.

18
00:00:54.759 --> 00:00:57.747
And then they would send the same program

19
00:00:57.747 --> 00:01:00.854
to all these computers in the cluster.

20
00:01:00.854 --> 00:01:03.251
And each computer would run the program

21
00:01:03.251 --> 00:01:05.993
on its little piece of the file

22
00:01:05.993 --> 00:01:08.196
and send the results back.

23
00:01:08.196 --> 00:01:09.921
The results would then be sorted

24
00:01:09.921 --> 00:01:13.034
and those results would
then be redistributed

25
00:01:13.034 --> 00:01:15.799
back to another process.

26
00:01:15.799 --> 00:01:19.251
The first process is called
a map or a mapper process

27
00:01:19.251 --> 00:01:21.946
and the second one was
called a reduce process.

28
00:01:21.946 --> 00:01:23.768
Fairly simple concepts

29
00:01:23.768 --> 00:01:25.770
but turned out that you could do

30
00:01:25.770 --> 00:01:28.316
lots and lots of different kinds of

31
00:01:28.316 --> 00:01:31.515
handle lots and lots of
different kinds of problems

32
00:01:31.515 --> 00:01:34.452
and very, very, very large data sets.

33
00:01:34.452 --> 00:01:38.043
So the one thing that's nice
about these big data clusters

34
00:01:38.043 --> 00:01:40.264
is they scale linearly.

35
00:01:40.264 --> 00:01:42.041
You had twice as many servers

36
00:01:42.041 --> 00:01:43.694
and you get twice the performance

37
00:01:43.694 --> 00:01:45.905
and you can handle twice
the amount of data.

38
00:01:45.905 --> 00:01:47.867
So this was just broke a bottleneck

39
00:01:47.867 --> 00:01:51.967
for all the major social media companies.

40
00:01:51.967 --> 00:01:54.251
Yahoo then got on board.

41
00:01:54.251 --> 00:01:57.388
Yahoo hired someone named Doug Cutting

42
00:01:57.388 --> 00:01:59.701
who had been working

43
00:01:59.701 --> 00:02:02.890
on a clone or a copy

44
00:02:02.890 --> 00:02:06.060
of the Google big data architecture

45
00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:07.750
and now that's called Hadoop.

46
00:02:07.750 --> 00:02:10.502
And if you google Hadoop you'll see that

47
00:02:10.502 --> 00:02:12.593
it's now a very popular term

48
00:02:12.593 --> 00:02:14.385
and there are many, many, many

49
00:02:14.385 --> 00:02:17.637
if you look at the big data ecology

50
00:02:17.637 --> 00:02:21.183
there are hundreds of thousands
of companies out there

51
00:02:21.183 --> 00:02:23.402
that have some kind of footprint

52
00:02:23.402 --> 00:02:25.235
in the big data world.

53
