54
00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:33.480
Most of the components of data
science have been around for

55
00:02:33.490 --> 00:02:35.860
many, many, many, many decades.

56
00:02:35.875 --> 00:02:38.110
But they're all coming together now

57
00:02:38.110 --> 00:02:41.940
with some new nuances I guess.

58
00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:43.520
At the bottom of data science

59
00:02:43.521 --> 00:02:46.469
you see probability and statistics.

60
00:02:46.469 --> 00:02:50.992
You see algebra, linear algebra

61
00:02:50.992 --> 00:02:52.879
you see programming

62
00:02:52.879 --> 00:02:54.667
and you see databases.

63
00:02:54.667 --> 00:02:57.243
They've all been here.

64
00:02:57.243 --> 00:02:59.756
But what's happened now is we

65
00:02:59.756 --> 00:03:02.873
now have the computational capabilities

66
00:03:02.873 --> 00:03:06.011
to apply some new techniques
- machine learning.

67
00:03:06.011 --> 00:03:08.865
Where now we can take really large data sets

68
00:03:08.865 --> 00:03:11.152
and instead of taking a sample

69
00:03:11.152 --> 00:03:14.539
and trying to test some hypothesis

70
00:03:14.539 --> 00:03:17.017
we can take really, really large data sets

71
00:03:17.017 --> 00:03:19.236
and look for patterns.

72
00:03:19.236 --> 00:03:23.785
And so back off one level
from hypothesis testing

73
00:03:23.785 --> 00:03:28.761
to finding patterns that maybe
will generate hypotheses.

74
00:03:28.761 --> 00:03:32.779
Now this can bother some very
traditional statisticians

75
00:03:32.779 --> 00:03:34.931
and gets them really annoyed sometimes

76
00:03:34.931 --> 00:03:36.962
that you know you're
supposed to have a hypothesis

77
00:03:36.962 --> 00:03:39.752
that is not that is
independent of the data

78
00:03:39.752 --> 00:03:40.753
and then you test it.

79
00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:45.940
So once some of these machine
learning techniques started

80
00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:47.860
were really the only thing

81
00:03:47.876 --> 00:03:49.472
the only way you can analyze

82
00:03:49.472 --> 00:03:51.368
some of these really large

83
00:03:51.368 --> 00:03:54.600
social media data sets.

84
00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:59.180
So what we've seen is that the combination

85
00:03:59.180 --> 00:04:04.240
of traditional [technique] areas computer science

86
00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:07.178
probability, statistics, mathematics

87
00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:12.320
all coming together in
this thing that we call

88
00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:13.977
Decision Sciences.

89
00:04:13.977 --> 00:04:15.215
Our department at Stern

90
00:04:15.215 --> 00:04:16.740
I'll give a little plug here

91
